[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.10: Clinical Trial Recruitment Conversationalist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2-9 per active prospective-participant per month (depends on trial mix, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, EHR-cohort-matching depth, and coordinator-handoff overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is 47. She has metastatic triple-negative breast cancer that progressed on first-line chemotherapy nine months after her initial diagnosis, and she has just had the conversation every patient in her position dreads, the one where her oncologist said the words "we should talk about a clinical trial." Maria is not a researcher. She is an accountant who, until a year ago, had never spent more than thirty minutes in a year thinking about the U.S. clinical-research enterprise. She left her oncologist's office with a printed sheet that listed five trials her oncologist thought might be appropriate, an encouraging hand-squeeze, and a directive to "call the research coordinators at the numbers on the sheet." That night, after her two children went to bed, Maria sat at her kitchen table and tried to figure out what came next.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trial 1 was at a major academic cancer center forty minutes from her house. The recruitment page on ClinicalTrials.gov was 2,400 words long and contained twenty-three inclusion criteria and nineteen exclusion criteria, several of which Maria did not understand. She wrote down questions: what does "ECOG performance status 0-1" mean? She had measurable disease, she thought, but she didn't know how the trial defined "measurable." She was three months past her last brain MRI, and the trial required documented absence of brain metastases within six weeks. Did her last MRI count? Was she supposed to get another one before contacting the coordinator? The trial was a Phase 1b dose-finding combination of an investigational PARP inhibitor and an investigational immune-checkpoint blocker. Maria did not know what either of those things were and the recruitment page assumed she did.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trial 2 was a Phase 3 randomized trial of a second-line antibody-drug conjugate. The recruitment page was clearer, but it required that the patient have HER2-low expression confirmed by central pathology review, and Maria's pathology report from her local lab said HER2 0, and she did not know whether that disqualified her, qualified her, or required a re-test. The recruitment page mentioned that prior pembrolizumab was an exclusion. Maria had received pembrolizumab as part of her first-line regimen. She was not sure whether that meant she was definitely excluded, or whether the exclusion only applied to certain durations, or whether there was an exception. The recruitment page did not say.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trial 3 had been listed on ClinicalTrials.gov as recruiting, but when Maria called the number, the coordinator informed her that the slot was actually filled and the trial had paused enrollment two weeks ago. The ClinicalTrials.gov listing had not been updated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trial 4 was at a community oncology practice ninety minutes from her house. The recruitment page was a single paragraph. It did not list the inclusion or exclusion criteria. It listed a phone number. Maria called the number, was put on hold for eleven minutes, and was eventually transferred to a research nurse who took her name and number and said someone would call back. Nobody called back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Trial 5 was a Phase 2 trial that Maria thought, after struggling through the recruitment page for forty minutes, she might actually qualify for. She called the coordinator the next morning. The coordinator was friendly, asked Maria a series of pre-screening questions, took down her information, and said the next step would be to obtain her recent imaging and pathology and that she would call Maria back in three to five business days. Two weeks later, with no callback, Maria called again, was told the coordinator was on vacation and that someone else would follow up, and waited another ten days. By the time the coordinator reached out, Maria's oncologist had already enrolled her in a different trial because Maria's disease was progressing and they could not wait.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's experience is not unusual. It is, in fact, the median experience of a patient with serious illness who is referred to potentially-relevant clinical trials in the United States in 2026. Maria's experience is the experience that produces the well-documented statistic that <!-- TODO: verify; estimates of clinical trials terminated for inability to recruit a sufficient number of participants vary by therapy area and trial phase, with industry-aggregate figures commonly cited in the range of 15-30% of trials terminating for recruitment-related reasons --> a meaningful fraction of clinical trials terminate or are amended for failure to recruit. It is the experience that produces the equally-documented statistic that <!-- TODO: verify; estimates of patients with cancer who are aware of potentially-relevant clinical trials but do not enroll vary by source and methodology, with several published studies reporting that a large majority of eligible patients do not enroll for reasons that include awareness, access, communication, and logistics --> the majority of patients with cancer who could plausibly enroll in a trial do not enroll, and that the gap is dominated by patients who never learned about a relevant trial in time, patients who tried to learn about a relevant trial and could not navigate the recruitment material, patients who tried to contact a coordinator and did not connect, and patients who connected but were lost in the screening pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The patient side of this story is the visible side. The site side, the sponsor side, and the coordinator side are equally broken. Research coordinators at trial sites are a small, dedicated, under-resourced workforce. A community-cancer-center coordinator typically supports between four and twelve open trials, fields between fifty and two hundred prospective-participant inquiries per month per active trial, and is the human bottleneck for every step from initial inquiry through screening through consent through enrollment. The coordinator's day is pre-screening calls, document collection, scheduling visits, coordinating with the local PI, communicating with sponsor monitors, completing case-report forms, managing protocol amendments, and (in the time that remains) building the relationships with patients that make people actually enroll.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The work the coordinators do that they do not do well, because they do not have the time, is the front of the funnel: returning the calls of patients who left messages, walking patients through inclusion and exclusion criteria, helping patients understand whether they are likely to qualify before scheduling an in-person screening, coordinating with the patient's referring oncologist for records, surfacing trials in the institutional portfolio that patients with their condition might not have heard of, and (especially) reaching the patients who did not call in the first place. Most coordinators describe this front-of-funnel work as the part of their job that suffers most when their workload is high.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The sponsor side has the same problem viewed from a different angle. A sponsor running a multi-site trial measures days-to-first-patient-in, screen-failure rate, screen-to-enroll conversion, and total enrollment against the protocol's projected timeline. When recruitment is slow, the sponsor's costs increase (because the trial runs longer), the protocol may need amending (because populations shift), and the sponsor may close the trial early (because the read-out window has passed). A trial that fails to recruit cannot answer the scientific question it was designed to answer, which means the patients who did enroll were exposed to research risk for no scientific benefit, which is among the most serious ethical failures in clinical research.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The IRB and the regulatory framework around recruitment communication add a constraint that is structurally important and operationally heavy. Recruitment material that goes to potential participants is reviewed and approved by the IRB. Material that is not IRB-approved cannot be used for recruitment. Material that contains coercive or undue-influence language, that overstates the potential benefit, that understates the risks, that targets vulnerable populations inappropriately, or that promises specific outcomes is not approvable. Material that is approved must be tracked, version-controlled, and used only in the form approved. The IRB's role here is the patient-protection floor, and the floor is institutional, not optional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The intersection of these problems, the patients who can't navigate the material, the coordinators who can't keep up with the front of the funnel, the sponsors who can't recruit fast enough, the IRBs who must approve everything that goes to participants, is one of the structural reasons clinical research progresses more slowly than the underlying science permits, why some therapy areas have an apparently-large therapeutic-development pipeline that nonetheless takes years longer than its peers to deliver an answer, and why the clinical-research enterprise has been searching, for at least two decades, for tools that can broaden the front of the funnel, deliver IRB-approved content to potential participants in plain language, pre-screen at population scale before consuming a coordinator's time, and surface the right trial to the right patient at the right moment. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on clinical-trial recruitment, including reports from the Tufts Center for the Study of Drug Development, the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, FDA-public-meetings on diversity and inclusion in clinical trials, and individual sponsor and academic-center publications, documents the recruitment challenges, the impact on trial timelines and costs, and the equity gaps in trial participation -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of digital tools attempted to address recruitment with patient-facing trial-search portals (ClinicalTrials.gov-derivatives with cleaner search), with site-level patient-recruitment software (CRMs for the front of the funnel), with EHR-integrated trial-matching products (cohort-matching against the institution's chart data), and with site-network platforms (multi-site coordination and central screening). These tools helped at the margins. They did not change the shape of the problem. The fundamental mismatch was that the recruitment material remained dense and clinical, the patient-facing portals remained clunky, the eligibility-criteria parsing remained mostly-manual, the pre-screening conversation remained a coordinator's job, and the equity gap remained largely untouched. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on clinical-trial recruitment technology including patient-facing trial-search portals, EHR-integrated cohort-matching tools, site-management platforms, and patient-recruitment CRMs documents partial improvements that have not closed the recruitment gap at scale -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023, is that conversational AI got good enough to act, in the right product design, as the front-of-funnel pre-screening and education layer that the coordinator workforce cannot afford to staff at population scale. A clinical trial recruitment conversationalist cannot replace the coordinator, the site PI, the IRB, the informed-consent process, or the patient's relationship with their treating oncologist. What it can do, when it is built carefully and governed appropriately, is take the dense IRB-approved recruitment material and convert it into a plain-language conversational explanation, walk a patient through the inclusion and exclusion criteria as questions rather than as a wall of text, gather the structured pre-screening responses, surface them to a coordinator in a form the coordinator can act on, hand off warmly when the patient wants to talk to a person, and (this is the part that is genuinely new) reach the patients who would not have called at all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that conversationalist. The clinical trial recruitment conversationalist is the conversational AI use case where several patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes converge (FAQ bot's input safety, scope discipline, and audit; intake bot's structured-question elicitation; insurance benefits navigator's external-data integration with provenance; mental-health bot's continuous emergency screening and warm handoff; care coordination assistant's longitudinal context and care-team reporting), and where several entirely new patterns enter the picture: IRB-approved recruitment-material discipline as architectural primitive, eligibility-criteria modeling at scale across an institutional or sponsor trial portfolio, EHR-cohort-matching for outreach with patient-consent-and-research-purpose-of-use governance, informed-consent-process boundaries (the conversationalist explains studies and pre-screens; informed consent is conducted by the consenting investigator), HIPAA "preparatory to research" versus "authorization-required" data-use pathways, sponsor-IRB-site coordination in multi-site deployments, equity-in-trials monitoring as launch-gate metric, and a level of recruitment-material-version-stamping and audit discipline that exceeds the patient-engagement-only bots.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that engages a patient or prospective participant in a conversation about a specific clinical trial or a portfolio of clinical trials, explains what the trial is designed to study, walks the patient through the inclusion and exclusion criteria as a guided pre-screening conversation, surfaces a likely-eligible result with appropriate confidence framing, schedules a follow-up with a research coordinator when the patient is interested, hands off the captured pre-screening data to the coordinator for the formal screening visit, and supports the coordinator-led informed-consent process by handling the routine education and Q&A that surrounds it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the consenting investigator. Informed consent for a clinical trial is a documented, IRB-approved process conducted by a qualified investigator with appropriate training and credentials. The conversationalist explains the study, answers common questions, walks the patient through the consent form's content as education, and supports the consenting visit. The consent itself is a separate, documented event handled by a human investigator. The conversationalist does not collect, witness, or confirm informed consent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the principal investigator. The principal investigator is the medically-qualified individual responsible for the conduct of the trial at the site. The conversationalist routes clinical questions, eligibility ambiguities, adverse-event disclosures, and protocol-deviation concerns to the PI or to coordinators acting under PI supervision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. When the conversationalist detects an acute-symptom presentation during a recruitment conversation (a patient describes new severe pain, suspected cardiac symptoms, or other red-flag presentations), the conversationalist routes to the triage workflow or to the patient's treating clinician, and does not try to handle the acute concern in scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a mental-health support bot. Recipe 11.8 covers conversational mental-health support with crisis screening and warm handoff. Patients in active recruitment conversations sometimes disclose distress, suicidal ideation, or mental-health crisis. The conversationalist runs the same continuous emergency screening as the other patient-facing bots and routes appropriately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a care coordination assistant. Recipe 11.9 covers longitudinal care coordination across providers and organizations. The recruitment conversationalist may coexist with a care coordination assistant for the same patient; the two integrate but address different scopes (coordination versus research participation).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a marketing bot. Recruitment material is IRB-approved patient education, not marketing. The conversationalist's tone is informational, patient-respecting, and free of coercive or undue-influence language. Persuasive-pattern drift is a recurring failure mode in this category and is actively engineered against.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not an EHR replacement. The clinicians' charts remain the system of record for clinical care. The conversationalist may consume chart data with patient consent for cohort matching and pre-screening context; it does not write to the chart for clinical decisions, though it may write structured research-data records (e.g., FHIR ResearchSubject resources, FHIR Communication resources for the conversation log) per institutional policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the human research workforce. The coordinator workforce remains essential. The conversationalist extends the coordinator's reach into the front-of-funnel pre-screening and education work that the coordinator cannot afford to staff at population scale, freeing the coordinator to focus on the formal screening visit, the consenting process, the on-trial visit work, the protocol-amendment communications, and the relationship-building that drives actual enrollment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. A recruitment conversationalist for a Phase 1 first-in-human oncology trial is different from one for a Phase 3 cardiovascular outcomes trial. A conversationalist for a rare-disease registry-style study is different from one for an interventional pediatric trial. A conversationalist for an academic-cancer-center portfolio is different from one for a sponsor-led multi-site trial. Most institutions deploy a multi-trial conversationalist architecture with trial-specific protocol-content layered on a shared recruitment-conversation core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing recruitment software intersects with the Common Rule (45 CFR 46), 21 CFR Parts 50 and 56 (FDA's informed consent and IRB requirements for FDA-regulated research), HIPAA's research-use provisions including the "preparatory to research" pathway, state-specific research-and-privacy regulations, IRB-approved recruitment-material requirements, sponsor-protocol-and-monitoring requirements, and (where the trial involves digital-tool measurements) the FDA SaMD framework. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory landscape for clinical-trial recruitment software includes 45 CFR 46 (Common Rule), 21 CFR Parts 50, 54, and 56 (FDA informed consent, financial disclosure, and IRB regulations), HIPAA Privacy Rule research provisions including preparatory-to-research and waiver-of-authorization pathways, state-specific research-privacy and recruitment-communication regulations, IRB-approval requirements for recruitment material, sponsor-protocol governance, and FDA SaMD framework where applicable; specific obligations vary by trial, by sponsor, by site, and by jurisdiction --> The institutional IRB office is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years, not sprints. The IRB-material-as-code lifecycle is multi-quarter, the eligibility-criteria-modeling investment is multi-quarter per trial, the EHR-cohort-matching integration work is multi-quarter, the coordinator-workflow-integration work is multi-quarter, and the equity-and-outcome demonstration is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the conversationalist's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the cumulative effect of broadening the recruitment funnel: the patients reached who would not have called, the pre-screened patients delivered to the coordinator with structured data, the patients walked through education content who do not later call the coordinator with questions the conversationalist could have answered, the coordinator hours freed for the relationship work that drives enrollment, the diversity of the recruited population improving when the outreach reaches under-represented patients, and the trial timelines compressing when the front of the funnel is wider. A conversationalist evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A conversationalist evaluated on recruitment outcomes (front-of-funnel reach, pre-screen-to-screen conversion, screen-to-enroll conversion, time-to-first-patient-in, demographic representativeness, coordinator-time-saved) is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Recruitment Grounded In IRB-Approved Material, Eligibility-Criteria Models, and Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Clinical Trial Recruitment Has Resisted Digital Tools For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical trial recruitment, as a workflow, has been a referral-and-coordinator-call problem for several decades. The reason is structural. Recruitment requires asking, repeatedly across trials and across patients, "what is this trial designed to study, who is the right participant, what does this specific patient look like, do they meet the inclusion and exclusion criteria, are they interested, can they realistically participate, and what does the enrollment pathway look like for them?" The questions are specific to the trial. The questions for a Phase 1 dose-escalation trial are different from the questions for a Phase 3 randomized trial. The questions for a rare-disease natural-history study are different from the questions for a cardiovascular-outcomes trial. The questions are also patient-specific, depend on the patient's clinical history (which is heterogeneous and incompletely documented), and depend on the patient's preferences, logistics, and life circumstances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing research coordinators do, when they do this well, is hold a working model of each trial's protocol in their heads, supplemented by the IRB-approved recruitment material, the protocol document, the inclusion and exclusion criteria, the schedule of assessments, and the local-site logistics. They translate the trial's clinical content into plain language for each prospective participant, they walk the patient through the criteria as a conversation, they handle the routine questions the patient has, and they identify the patient-specific issues that need PI involvement (eligibility ambiguities, off-label-prior-treatment exclusions, comorbid-condition-impact judgments). Holding this model and delivering it conversationally is most of the cognitive work of front-of-funnel recruitment; the document collection and scheduling are the visible part, but the conversational translation work is the work that distinguishes a coordinator who recruits well from a coordinator who is busy but does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital recruitment products, roughly the early 2010s through the late 2010s, focused on patient-facing trial-search portals. ClinicalTrials.gov is the federally-mandated registry; commercial portals layered cleaner search and patient-friendlier presentation on top of it. The tools helped some patients find trials they would not otherwise have found. The tools did not address the wall-of-text recruitment-page problem, the eligibility-criteria-density problem, the coordinator-bottleneck problem, or the equity-of-outreach problem. <!-- TODO: verify; the patient-facing trial-search portal landscape includes ClinicalTrials.gov, commercial portals (some operated by sponsors, some by patient-advocacy organizations, some by independent companies), and disease-specific registries; effect on enrollment is documented as marginal absent additional intervention -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2017 to 2022, leveraged EHR data, FHIR APIs, and natural-language processing of trial protocols to build cohort-matching products: given an institution's chart data, identify which patients might be eligible for which trials in the institution's portfolio. These tools improved the site-side feasibility analysis and the targeting of physician-referrer outreach. They did not address the patient-facing communication problem (the matching identifies likely-eligible patients but does not handle the recruitment conversation), and they were uneven across institutions because the EHR-data-quality and the eligibility-criteria-modeling work were uneven.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can synthesize structured trial protocols, IRB-approved recruitment material, and patient-specific context into conversational explanations and pre-screening dialogues. The recruitment conversationalist, deployed with IRB-and-institutional governance, can hold the pre-screening conversation that the coordinator would have held, walk the patient through the IRB-approved material in plain language, gather structured pre-screening responses, surface them to the coordinator in a form the coordinator can act on, hand off warmly when the patient is ready, and reach the patients who would not have called at all. The LLM is not a coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets recruitment workflows that have historically required coordinator-hour-per-patient operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "patient navigates trial-search portal alone, coordinator picks up what comes through" to "conversationalist walks patient through IRB-approved material and pre-screens conversationally, coordinator picks up warm-handed pre-screened patients with structured data." The conversationalist's value is concentrated in three places: the IRB-approved material delivery (turning dense recruitment-page content into plain-language conversations grounded in cited IRB-approved sources), the structured pre-screening (turning inclusion-and-exclusion criteria into guided conversation with provenance for each response), and the operational reach (extending the coordinator workforce from the small fraction of prospective participants it serves today to the broader population that needs it but does not currently get it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Recruitment Conversationalist Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A recruitment conversationalist is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which conversationalist it is, the patient's authenticated context (where authentication is appropriate; un-authenticated browsing is also a supported entry path with reduced data scope), the relevant trial-portfolio context (which trials the institution is recruiting for, which trials the patient is likely-eligible for if cohort matching has been performed with consent), access to a structured library of IRB-approved recruitment material (recruitment pages, plain-language summaries, FAQ content, consent-form content for education purposes, schedule-of-assessments material), access to a structured library of eligibility-criteria models (the inclusion and exclusion criteria expressed both as IRB-approved free text and as structured predicates), and a careful set of tools for retrieving trial information, performing structured pre-screening, surfacing likely-eligible results, scheduling coordinator handoffs, posting expression-of-interest events, and escalating to coordinators or PIs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by a patient browsing a trial-search surface, sometimes by a patient referred by their treating clinician with a specific trial in mind, sometimes by a patient responding to an institution-and-IRB-approved outreach message about a trial they may be eligible for, sometimes by a patient returning to a previous conversation to follow up, and sometimes by a coordinator request to follow up with the patient on a specific item.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversationalist's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial discovery and education.** The patient enters the surface either with a specific trial in mind (referred by their clinician with a specific NCT number or sponsor protocol identifier) or in a browsing posture (searching by condition, by location, by phase, by sponsor, or by other criteria). The conversationalist surfaces matching trials from the institutional portfolio (with cross-portfolio search where the deployment is multi-institution), provides plain-language descriptions grounded in the IRB-approved material, answers common questions about trial design, phase, randomization, placebo (where applicable), schedule of assessments, time commitment, compensation (where applicable), and the patient's logistical fit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Initial-interest qualification.** Before walking the patient through the formal pre-screening criteria, the conversationalist may handle initial-interest qualification: does the patient have the underlying condition, are they in the relevant clinical context (e.g., progression on a prior line of therapy), is the trial's location feasible for them, do they have basic logistical fit. Initial qualification reduces the screening load on the formal pre-screening flow and reduces the patient's frustration if the trial is plainly inappropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured pre-screening conversation.** When the patient is interested in a specific trial and meets the initial-interest threshold, the conversationalist walks them through the trial's inclusion and exclusion criteria as a structured conversation. Each criterion is presented as a question (or a small set of questions) in plain language, with the patient's response captured as structured data. The conversationalist explains the criterion, answers the patient's questions about it within scope, and (where the patient does not know an answer) supports the patient in obtaining the information from their treating clinician's records or their own documents. The pre-screening flow is designed to maximize accurate self-report while respecting that some criteria require records-based confirmation that happens at the formal screening visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Likely-eligibility surfacing with appropriate framing.** At the end of the structured pre-screening, the conversationalist surfaces a likely-eligibility result. The result is framed conservatively: "Based on what you've told me, you appear to meet the basic criteria for this trial. The next step is a formal screening visit with the research coordinator, where they'll review your medical records and may run additional tests to confirm." The conversationalist does not promise eligibility, does not commit the patient to participation, and does not bypass the coordinator's screening visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Expression-of-interest capture and coordinator handoff.** When the patient indicates they would like to take the next step, the conversationalist captures the expression of interest, gathers the contact information needed for coordinator follow-up (per institutional policy and IRB approval), schedules a coordinator follow-up where supported, and posts a structured expression-of-interest event to the coordinator queue with the captured pre-screening data, the conversation excerpt, and the IRB-approved-material version stamps. The handoff is warm: the patient knows what to expect from the coordinator, when the coordinator will reach out, and what the coordinator's role is.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-question handling within scope.** The patient may have questions across the lifecycle: about the trial's design, the schedule of assessments, the time commitment, the placebo (where applicable), the randomization, the masking, the post-trial-access policy, the compensation policy (where applicable), the travel-and-logistical-support policy (where applicable), the data-use policy, the right to withdraw, and the patient's contact options if they have concerns during participation. The conversationalist answers within scope using grounded retrieval over the IRB-approved material and the institutional FAQ library. Out-of-scope questions (clinical recommendations beyond the trial, diagnosis-attempted, treatment-recommendation-attempted, mental-health crisis) route to the appropriate pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent-process education and support.** When a patient is interested and pre-screening is complete, the conversationalist supports the consent-process education: walks the patient through the consent-form content as plain-language explanation, answers questions about specific consent-form sections, and clarifies what the consent visit will involve. The conversationalist does not collect, witness, or confirm informed consent. The consent is a separate documented event with the consenting investigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outreach to likely-eligible patients with consent.** Where the institutional cohort-matching has identified patients in the institution's chart data who appear likely-eligible for a specific trial, and where the institution and IRB have approved targeted outreach for that trial, the conversationalist may initiate outbound messages that introduce the trial and invite the patient to a conversation. The outreach respects the patient's overall communication preferences, the institution's outreach policies, and the IRB's approved recruitment-material and approach. The outreach is an opt-in surface; patients who do not want it can opt out at any time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort and equity monitoring.** The conversationalist's reach is monitored per cohort: which patient populations are reached, which populations engage, which populations pre-screen, which populations are likely-eligible, which populations express interest, which populations show up to the formal screening visit, which populations enroll. The per-cohort metrics are reviewed to detect equity gaps and to inform outreach strategy and protocol-content revision.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-side reporting.** The coordinator receives structured reports: real-time alerts for high-priority handoffs (patients who appear likely-eligible for high-priority trials), daily digests of expression-of-interest events with pre-screening data, weekly summaries of trial-portfolio activity, ad-hoc lookups for specific patients. The reporting is designed for the coordinator's workflow and is reviewed by clinical-research leadership before launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor-side reporting where applicable.** Where the deployment includes sponsor-funded trials, the sponsor receives aggregate, IRB-approved metrics on trial-level recruitment activity (volume, time-to-first-patient-in, screen-failure rate, screen-to-enroll conversion, demographic distribution of enrolled population) without identifying individual prospective participants. Sponsor visibility is pre-specified in the institution's data-sharing agreements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Protocol-amendment handling.** When a trial's protocol is amended (changing eligibility criteria, schedule of assessments, study procedures, consent-form language), the new IRB-approved material is propagated through the conversationalist's content stores, version stamps update, prior conversations are preserved with their original version stamps, and the operational tooling reflects the change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Recruitment Conversationalist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in a trial's recruitment page, and have it answer recruitment questions. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, regulatory, and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no concept of IRB approval.** Recruitment material that goes to potential participants must be IRB-approved. A generic LLM trained on web text will produce content that paraphrases, embellishes, omits, and sometimes confabulates content from the source recruitment page. The IRB has not approved the paraphrase. The material the conversationalist delivers is therefore not IRB-approved, which is an institutional and regulatory failure independent of whether the paraphrase is accurate. The architectural primitive is delivering IRB-approved material verbatim or near-verbatim with explicit version stamps and citation back to the IRB-approved source, with paraphrase only where the paraphrase has been pre-approved or where the paraphrase is operationally bounded (e.g., the conversationalist may simplify reading level using pre-approved templates, but it does not invent recruitment content).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model produces persuasive language.** A generalist LLM, asked to engage a patient in a conversation about a trial, will produce content that is enthusiastic, that emphasizes the potential benefits, and that downplays the risks. This is the model's bias toward agreeableness, not malice. The output, in a recruitment context, is undue influence and coercive language; the IRB will not approve it; the material is clinically and ethically wrong. The architectural discipline is active engineering against the persuasive pattern, with system-prompt constraints, output-safety filters tagged for persuasive-pattern, sampled clinical review of conversations, and content-policy training data that explicitly demonstrates appropriate informational tone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no eligibility-criteria model.** Inclusion and exclusion criteria for clinical trials are dense, technical, and require structured reasoning. A generalist LLM asked "do I qualify for this trial" will produce a plausible-sounding answer that may or may not be correct and that does not carry the structured-data record needed for coordinator follow-up. The architectural primitive is the eligibility-criteria-as-structured-predicates layer, with each criterion modeled as a structured question (or small question set) backed by a deterministic predicate that produces a structured answer, with the LLM responsible for the conversational presentation and the patient-question handling, not for the criterion-satisfied determination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of out-of-date trial content.** Trials open, close, pause, amend their protocols, reopen, and terminate on timelines the LLM does not know. A generalist LLM trained on web text from a year ago will confidently describe a trial that closed last month. The architectural primitive is the trial-corpus registry as a real-time-or-near-real-time data store, with active/paused/closed status tracked, with protocol-amendment versioning, and with the conversationalist consuming the registry rather than its training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no cohort-matching capability.** Identifying which patients in an institution's chart data are likely-eligible for which trials in the portfolio requires structured matching against EHR data with appropriate consent and research-purpose-of-use governance. The LLM does not perform this matching; the cohort-matching subsystem performs it (using deterministic rules where the criteria are computable from chart data, using NLP-extraction where the criteria depend on free-text history, using human-validated annotations where the criteria require clinician judgment), and the LLM consumes the matching results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the consent process.** Informed consent is a documented IRB-approved process conducted by a qualified investigator. The LLM does not collect, witness, or confirm consent. The LLM supports consent-process education and Q&A; the consent itself is a separate event. The architectural primitive enforces the boundary: the conversationalist's tools include consent-form-content-retrieve and consent-question-answer, but do not include consent-collect or consent-witness. The handoff to the consenting investigator is explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of HIPAA's research-use pathways.** HIPAA's research-use provisions distinguish "preparatory to research" (chart-review for protocol feasibility and participant identification, with specific limits), "authorization-required research" (the patient signs an authorization permitting use of their PHI for the research), "waiver of authorization" (the IRB waives the authorization requirement under specific conditions), and "limited dataset" use cases. The conversationalist's data-use posture is calibrated to the specific trial and the specific institutional approach; the LLM does not reason about this and the architecture enforces the calibration. <!-- TODO: verify; HIPAA's research-use pathways including the preparatory-to-research provision (45 CFR 164.512(i)(1)(ii)), authorization-required research, IRB waiver of authorization (45 CFR 164.512(i)(2)), and limited dataset (45 CFR 164.514(e)) are detailed in the HIPAA Privacy Rule with continued OCR and IRB guidance -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the recruitment-material lifecycle.** Recruitment material moves through a lifecycle: drafted, IRB-reviewed, IRB-approved with effective date, in use, amended, IRB-re-approved, retired. The conversationalist's content store reflects this lifecycle. The LLM does not invent material; the LLM delivers the material that is currently IRB-approved-and-in-use, with version stamping that ties each conversation to the specific approved version.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** Eligibility logic includes time-window calculations (was the prior treatment within the protocol-specified window?), measurement-comparison calculations (does the patient's measurement meet the protocol-specified threshold?), counting calculations (how many prior lines of therapy?), and similar structured arithmetic. The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic eligibility-rule engine encapsulates the computation; the LLM hands off arithmetic to the engine and consumes the structured result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equity-in-trials.** Clinical trials have well-documented equity gaps: under-representation of racial and ethnic minorities, under-representation of older adults, under-representation of low-income participants, under-representation of patients in rural areas, under-representation of patients with limited English proficiency. <!-- TODO: verify; clinical-trial diversity and inclusion data are documented in FDA, NIH, sponsor, and academic-center publications, with continued attention from FDA's Diversity Plans guidance, the Diversity Action Plans framework, and ongoing sponsor and IRB initiatives --> A conversationalist that reaches preferentially the patients who already would have been recruited is a conversationalist that exacerbates rather than reduces the equity gap. The architectural discipline is per-cohort outreach monitoring and per-cohort engagement monitoring with launch-gate thresholds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the sponsor-IRB-site coordination.** Multi-site trials involve a sponsor, a central IRB or multiple local IRBs, the participating sites, the site PIs, the coordinators, and (where outsourced) a contract research organization. Each has roles, deliverables, and visibility constraints. The conversationalist's data-flow respects the contracted boundaries; the LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope when the patient asks for clinical recommendations.** Patients in recruitment conversations frequently bring up clinical questions: should they enroll, would the trial be better than their current treatment, what does their oncologist think, what should they do about a symptom they have. The conversationalist answers within scope (here is the trial's design; here is what the trial is studying; the comparison to your current treatment is a question for your treating clinician) and routes outside scope (this is a clinical question for your treating clinician; here is the route).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to recruitment.** The conversation contains sensitive disclosures about the patient's clinical situation, prior treatments, comorbidities, and personal context. The audit, retention, access-control, sponsor-visibility-bounded, IRB-reportable-event handling, and downstream-research-workflow integration story has to handle each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of relationship preservation when the patient is not eligible.** A patient who has spent twenty minutes in a conversation about a trial they hoped to be eligible for, who is then told they do not appear to qualify, is in an emotionally difficult moment. The conversationalist's tone, the alternative-trial offering (where there are alternatives), the warm pathway to a coordinator who can confirm or look further, and the explicit acknowledgment that the patient's effort is appreciated, are part of the architecture, not afterthoughts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Recruitment Conversationalist Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification (where authenticated; the recruitment surface also supports unauthenticated browsing with reduced data scope), tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading where authenticated, citation grounding, behavior-aware tone calibration, crisis-pathway routing. The recruitment conversationalist adds nine structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved recruitment-material as system of record for participant-facing content.** Every patient-facing recruitment message, plain-language description, FAQ answer, and consent-education content has an IRB-approved source with a recorded version stamp. The conversation log captures the version stamps. The conversationalist does not produce participant-facing recruitment content outside this lineage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility-criteria-as-structured-predicates with deterministic logic.** Each inclusion and exclusion criterion is modeled as a structured predicate with deterministic evaluation against patient-reported and (where consented) chart-derived data. The structured-predicate layer is institutional content, signed off by clinical-research leadership and the IRB, version-controlled, and audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-corpus registry with real-time-or-near-real-time status tracking.** The trial portfolio is a curated registry with active/paused/closed status, IRB-approval status, recruitment-material version, eligibility-criteria-model version, and operational-availability flags. The conversationalist consumes the registry; it does not infer trial status.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort-matching as separate subsystem with consent-and-purpose-of-use governance.** Cohort matching against EHR data is performed by a separate subsystem operating under explicit consent-and-purpose-of-use governance (preparatory-to-research, authorization-required, IRB-waiver-of-authorization, limited dataset, as appropriate per trial). The cohort-matching results inform outreach and surface likely-eligible trials during conversation. The cohort-matching is auditable, version-stamped, and reviewed for equity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent-process boundary enforcement.** The conversationalist's tools support consent-process education and Q&A; the conversationalist does not collect, witness, or confirm informed consent. The handoff to the consenting investigator is explicit and documented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-handoff pathway as production scope.** The handoff from conversationalist to coordinator is a first-class workflow with structured pre-screening data delivered, conversation excerpts attached, IRB-approved-material version stamps preserved, coordinator-availability awareness, and follow-up scheduling integrated. Under-investing in the handoff workflow under-uses the conversationalist; the coordinator is the consumer of the conversationalist's output, and the workflow integration is the link.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor-IRB-site contracted boundaries.** In multi-site or sponsor-funded deployments, the data-flow respects the contracted boundaries: which data the sponsor sees, which the central IRB sees, which the local IRB sees, which the site sees, which the patient sees. The architecture enforces the boundaries; the LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-in-trials monitoring with launch-gate discipline.** Outreach reach, engagement, pre-screen, expression-of-interest, screen-show, and enrollment metrics are monitored per cohort (race, ethnicity, age cohort, sex, socioeconomic context, language, geography). Per-cohort dashboards are reviewed by clinical-research leadership, IRB, equity leadership, and patient-advocacy. Launch-gate thresholds for per-cohort metrics are established before deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation against recruitment-specific outcomes.** The conversationalist's performance is measured against outcomes that reflect recruitment quality: front-of-funnel reach, pre-screen-to-screen conversion, screen-to-enroll conversion, time-to-first-patient-in, demographic representativeness of enrolled population, coordinator-time-saved, patient-reported recruitment experience.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle (where authenticated; with un-authenticated browsing as a parallel surface), conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Recruitment Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes clinical-trial recruitment specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved recruitment material is the product.** Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that their recruitment material was not designed for conversational delivery and needs work to be appropriate. Plain-language summaries reviewed by patient-advocacy. Reading-level adjustments validated against the target population. Multi-language translations validated by language-services and IRB. FAQ content covering the questions patients actually ask. Consent-form-content for education purposes excerpted with IRB approval. Formalizing this is multi-quarter clinical-research-leadership work that has to start before the engineering work and continue alongside it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility-criteria modeling is the second-largest investment.** Each trial's inclusion and exclusion criteria need structured representation. Some criteria are computable from chart data (age, lab values, prior diagnoses, prior treatments). Some require patient self-report (current symptoms, willingness to comply with study procedures, willingness to travel). Some require records-based confirmation at the formal screening visit (specific imaging within a window, central pathology review, specific molecular markers). Modeling each criterion appropriately, with clear accountability for each, is multi-quarter work per trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort-matching has well-known data-quality challenges.** EHR data is incomplete, inconsistent, and varies across institutions. A patient's prior treatment may be in the chart, in the chart's free-text history, in a referring provider's records, in the claims data, or absent. Cohort-matching that relies on structured chart data alone misses patients; cohort-matching that uses NLP extraction has accuracy ceilings; cohort-matching that requires manual annotation does not scale. The architecture combines structured rules, NLP extraction, and human-validated annotations with explicit accuracy estimates per criterion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Persuasive-pattern drift is a recurring failure mode.** A generalist LLM, asked to engage prospective participants enthusiastically, will produce coercive or undue-influence language. Sampled conversation review by IRB-trained reviewers tags persuasive-pattern as a failure mode. The system prompt, output safety, persona-and-tone evaluator, and conversation-review process specifically watch for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-in-trials is a measurable outcome the conversationalist can directly affect.** Trial populations that under-represent specific demographic groups produce evidence with limited applicability to those groups, which is a clinical and ethical failure. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on clinical-trial diversity, including the FDA Diversity Action Plan framework, the NIH Inclusion across the Lifespan policy, and individual-sponsor and academic-center data, documents persistent under-representation of racial and ethnic minorities, older adults, women in some specialties, low-income participants, rural participants, and participants with limited English proficiency --> A conversationalist that broadens outreach to under-represented populations is a conversationalist that measurably improves equity-in-trials in a way that single-site recruitment efforts cannot. The per-cohort outreach metrics and the per-cohort enrollment metrics are launch-gate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordinator workflow integration is structurally important.** Coordinators are the consumers of the conversationalist's output. A handoff that delivers structured pre-screening data, conversation excerpts, IRB-approved-material version stamps, and coordinator-actionable next steps is a handoff that the coordinator uses. A handoff that delivers a free-text summary that the coordinator has to re-process is a handoff that the coordinator does not use. The handoff format is co-designed with coordinator workforce leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-portfolio breadth varies by institution.** A major academic cancer center may run hundreds of open trials; a community-cancer-center may run a dozen; a sponsor-led multi-site network has its own portfolio shape. The architecture supports portfolio diversity, with per-trial protocol-content, per-trial eligibility-criteria-models, per-trial recruitment-material, and per-trial coordinator-workforce mapping.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor visibility is contracted, not assumed.** What the sponsor sees about prospective-participant interactions is pre-specified in the institution's data-sharing agreements with the sponsor. Aggregate metrics yes; identifying information no, except where the patient has consented to sponsor data-sharing as part of the consent process. The architecture enforces the contracted boundaries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Protocol amendments are operationally significant.** A trial whose eligibility criteria change after IRB approval triggers updates to the recruitment material, the eligibility-criteria-model, the FAQ content, the consent-form-content for education purposes, and the conversationalist's content store. Amendments may require re-IRB-approval before in-progress conversations can use the new material. The conversationalist's protocol-amendment-handling discipline is multi-quarter operational work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sensitive disclosures are common during recruitment.** Patients in recruitment conversations sometimes disclose information that triggers other pathways: acute symptoms (route to the patient's treating clinician), mental-health distress (route per recipe 11.8), suspected abuse (route per institutional mandatory-reporting), sensitive-record content (substance use, mental health, HIV status; route per state and 42 CFR Part 2 where applicable). The continuous emergency screening and sensitive-disclosure detection patterns from previous recipes apply, with recruitment-specific calibration for the kinds of disclosures that are common in this surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The recruitment-conversation surface is heterogeneous across channels.** Patients enter recruitment conversations through web chat (institutional or trial-specific microsite), through SMS (where the institution and IRB have approved SMS as a recruitment channel and the patient has consented to SMS communication), through in-app chat (institutional patient app), through voice (where supported), and through clinician-mediated entry (the clinician hands the patient a tablet during a clinic visit). The architecture supports the heterogeneity with channel-specific consent posture, channel-specific session management, and channel-specific accessibility considerations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment is subject to per-language IRB approval.** Recruitment material in a language other than English is IRB-approved per language. Translations are reviewed by language-services and IRB before deployment. The per-language asset development is part of production scope; the per-language launch-gate is a formal IRB-approved-translation-and-clinical-validation step, not just engineering work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational data integration matters where the institution recruits across systems.** A community-cancer-center recruiting into a sponsor's multi-site trial may consume the patient's records from the academic-center where the patient was originally treated, the local imaging center, the local pharmacy, and the local lab. The cross-organizational data integration patterns from recipe 11.9 apply, with research-purpose-of-use calibration and IRB approval for the data-flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is multi-year work.** The conversationalist's effect on front-of-funnel reach shows up over weeks to months. The effect on pre-screen-to-screen conversion shows up over months. The effect on screen-to-enroll conversion shows up over months. The effect on demographic representativeness of the enrolled population shows up over months to a year. The effect on time-to-first-patient-in and the overall trial timeline shows up over the duration of the trial, which is years. The effect on the institution's overall recruitment-success rate, on the sponsor's portfolio recruitment rate, and on clinical-research progress in specific therapy areas shows up over years to decades. Institutions building this with quarterly-impact expectations will be disappointed; institutions willing to invest at the right time horizon can demonstrate genuinely meaningful outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The FDA Diversity Action Plan framework has raised the explicit bar on demographic representativeness.** The FDA's 2024 Diversity Action Plan guidance and the related provisions of the Food and Drug Omnibus Reform Act of 2022 require sponsors of certain pivotal trials to submit Diversity Action Plans documenting how the trial will recruit a population representative of the disease's patient population. <!-- TODO: verify; the Diversity Action Plan framework derives from FDORA 2022 with FDA implementation guidance evolving; specific provisions, applicability, and effective dates are documented in FDA publications and continue to update --> Sponsors and sites are increasingly accountable for demographic recruitment metrics; conversationalist deployments that contribute to broader outreach are operating in a more demanding regulatory environment than equivalent deployments a decade ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ClinicalTrials.gov modernization continues.** ClinicalTrials.gov remains the federally-mandated registry. The 2022 modernization efforts and continued updates aim to make the registry more accessible to patients and to improve data quality. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov modernization is a multi-year NIH-led effort with continued releases of the modernized platform --> Conversationalists consuming the registry consume the modern API where available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR resources for research are increasingly mature.** The FHIR ResearchStudy, ResearchSubject, and Group resources, plus the broader implementation guides for clinical-trial data exchange (CDISC integration with FHIR, Vulcan accelerator efforts, IDMP), are improving the data-exchange substrate. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR research-related resources include ResearchStudy, ResearchSubject, Group, ActivityDefinition, PlanDefinition, and others, with implementation guides under continued development through HL7 and the Vulcan FHIR Accelerator --> Conversationalists integrating with research data infrastructure consume FHIR research resources where available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EHR-integrated trial-matching products are deployed at most major academic centers.** The cohort-matching products (commercial and academic) have continued to mature. <!-- TODO: verify; EHR-integrated trial-matching products are deployed at most major academic medical centers, with documented studies of the patterns of use, the ways the matching results inform recruitment, and the limitations of automated matching --> The conversationalist deployments build on these products as the cohort-matching substrate where available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-facing trial-search portals have improved but remain incomplete.** ClinicalTrials.gov, sponsor-led portals, patient-advocacy-led portals, and disease-specific registries serve different segments of the trial-search user population. The conversationalist deployments often integrate with multiple portals to broaden reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle recruitment conversations well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to recruitment work. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial-corpus entries, retrieve eligibility criteria, retrieve IRB-approved material with version stamping, perform structured pre-screening, surface likely-eligibility, capture expression of interest, schedule coordinator follow-up, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-coordinator deployment is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI conversationalist for the front-of-funnel pre-screening and education, with human coordinators for the formal screening visit, consenting process, on-trial visits, and PI-level decisions. The economics work because the conversationalist handles the high-volume, low-judgment-requirement front-of-funnel work while the coordinator focuses on where their judgment and relationship-building matter most.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive.** Studies of digital-recruitment-augmentation deployments have shown improvements in front-of-funnel reach, pre-screen-to-screen conversion, and (in some studies) demographic representativeness. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for digital recruitment augmentation includes published studies from sponsors, academic centers, and recruitment-platform vendors; specific outcome figures vary by study and are sensitive to baseline performance, trial mix, and deployment maturity --> The ROI demonstrations are stronger when the analysis includes downstream-outcome metrics (enrollments, time-to-first-patient-in, demographic representativeness) than when the analysis focuses only on conversation-volume metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity attention is rising.** Federal and IRB attention to clinical-trial diversity has increased, and conversationalist deployments are increasingly evaluated on per-cohort outreach and engagement metrics. The launch-gate discipline reflects this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some recruitment segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer recruitment-platform products with FHIR integration, trial-matching, IRB-material-management, coordinator-workflow integration, and (in some cases) AI conversation surfaces. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for the trial-matching substrate, the IRB-material lifecycle management, the coordinator-CRM, and the recruitment-analytics, and integrate with the institution's clinical-research, EHR, and patient-engagement infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
